==English==

===Etymology===
First attested around 1472. From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{term|absurdite|lang=enm}},<ref name=RHD>{{R:RHCD|page=7}}</ref> then from '''either''' {{etyl|frm|en}} {{term|absurdité|lang=frm}}, '''or''' from {{etyl|LL.|en}} {{term|absurditas||dissonance, incongruity|lang=la}}, from {{etyl|la|en}} {{term|absurdus|lang=la}} + {{suffix||itas|quality, state, degree|lang=la}}.<ref name=WI3>{{R:MW3 1976|page=8}}</ref><ref name=SOED>{{R:SOED5|page=10}}</ref> Equivalent to {{suffix|absurd|ity}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|RP}} {{IPA|/əbˈsɝd.ɪ.ti/}}
* {{a|US}} {{IPA|/æbˈsɝd.ɪ.ti/|/æbˈzɝd.ɪ.ti/|/əbˈsɝd.ɪ.ti/|/əbˈzɝd.ɪ.ti/}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun|~|absurdities}}

# {{context|obsolete|rare|lang=en}} [[dissonance|Dissonance]]. {{defdate|Attested from around 1350 to 1470 until the late 17<sup>th</sup> century.}}<ref name=SOED/>
# {{context|countable|lang=en}} That which is absurd; an absurd action; a [[logical]] [[contradiction]]. {{defdate|First attested in the late 15<sup>th</sup> century.}}<ref name=SOED/>
#* His travels were full of '''absurdities'''. - Johnson
# {{context|uncountable|lang=en}} The quality of being absurd or [[inconsistent]] with [[obvious]] truth, reason, or sound judgment. {{defdate|First attested in the early 16<sup>th</sup> century.}}<ref name=SOED/>
#* The '''absurdity''' of the actual idea of an infinite number. - [[w:John Locke|John Locke]]
#* {{RQ:Schuster Hepaticae V|viii}}
#*: Neither [Jones]{{...}} nor I (in 1966) could conceive of reducing our "science" to the ultimate '''absurdity''' of reading Finnish newspapers almost a century and a half old in order to establish "priority."

